I was just completing, then. Which is pretty much of a very impotant point: Take any developer, it is not good, if not
catastrophic, uif that developer has no clue how his developed features are packaged for production. And why. It feel
it especially is true in the context: any person watching the video, willing to work in front web dev, has to hear about
the packaging, eg, how do you work/test while you work with sass / less . css ? All in all, the CDN stuff is a
dependency of the front web developer's work. As such, it i, I think, a most important thing for him to be curious
about it.

Indeed a CDN is specifically implemented with servers ideally spread around the world. The purpose is to keep multiple
caches of often reused files & route the traffic to the closest server thus minimizing latency. Familiarity with CDN's
doesn't magically impart knowledge of Bootstrap or any other of the 10,001 web frameworks out there so this is still a
worthwhile view to anyone.

One more worth to mention, , very much so, I believe, characteristics of today's CDN service  offer: What Mr. Sticky ...
is that there is some caching alon,g the routing. Well, today's CDN offers propose you this : Your web site stays on
line, ... EVenn if your provider shut down your server!...
